"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423213","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-29","<p><strong></strong></p><br /> <br /><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) aims to build digital services that are simpler, clearer and faster to use. In 2013-14 and 2014-15 BIS took the lead in developing five exemplar “digital by default”projects. These focused on transforming key areas in which BIS engages with the public: student finance, Land Registry data, renewing patents, redundancy payments and apprenticeships. By the end of 2014-15 all five BIS digital exemplars were either live or in trial(“beta”) use.</p><br /><p>Each of these is starting to bring significant benefits. For example, each year there are around 400,000 transactions for renewals of patents. The new digital patent renewal service allows patent owners and agents to complete the renewal process online in just a few minutes whereas the older, paper based service took up to 6 days to process.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-29T15:25:38.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423213/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423213/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-22","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of efficiency savings arising from his Department's digital strategies in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","13087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423214","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-29","<br /><p>The Government is committed to fair and simple levy arrangements. We are working closely with Her Majesty’s Treasury and Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs on the design and implementation of the levy. Further detail will be set out alongside the Spending Review later in the autumn.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-29T17:47:36.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423214/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423214/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-22","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the proportion of the funds generated through the proposed apprenticeship levy which will be required for its administration costs.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","13091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423215","Women and Equalities","false","2015-10-27","<p>The gender pay gap has fallen to its lowest ever level, and our ambition is to eliminate it within a generation. That is why we will require large employers to publish information on the differences between men and women’s’ pay and bonuses. Gender pay gap reporting will also be extended to the public sector. We will continue taking action to inspire girls and young women; modernise workplaces; and support older working women.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2015-10-27T16:32:45.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423215/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423215/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2015-10-22","Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what plans her Department has to close the gender pay gap.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","13095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423216","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-27","<br /> <br /><p>We have consulted on our proposals to devolve the power to extend Sunday trading hours to local areas, to which we received a large number of responses from a wide range of stakeholders. We will be publishing the Government’s response shortly. In the consultation, we said we considered that devolving this power would enable local areas to determine the Sunday trading hours that better reflect the need of local people, providing greater choice over when and where they shop. People may choose small retailers, as for example, they offer a diverse range of products and services from convenient locations. This is perhaps why the convenience sector last year saw the opening of two new stores a day and growth in turnover of 5%.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-27T14:19:39.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423216/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423216/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-22","Small Businesses: Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what research his Department has commissioned or undertaken to assess the potential effect on small businesses of proposed changes to Sunday trading laws.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","13098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423217","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Department for Education (DfE) and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS), along with respective funding agencies, have re-prioritised staffing resources to support the review of post-16 education and training.</p><br /><p>There are seven reviews in the first wave of area reviews which have either launched since September or will launch in the next few weeks. Each review will take 3-4 months to complete and will be supported by resource from the DfE, BIS, Education Funding Agency and Skills Funding Agency.</p><br /><p>The area reviews of post 16 education and training are being undertaken in waves and can be triggered by either the local area requesting a review or the FE Commissioner or Sixth Form College Commissioner identifying the need for a review because one or more colleges in an area are at risk of failing. The first wave is underway now and details of the following reviews have been announced and can be found on the gov.uk website :</p><br /><p>Birmingham and Solihull</p><p>Greater Manchester</p><p>Sheffield City Region</p><p>Tees Valley</p><p>Sussex Coast</p><p>Solent</p><p>West Yorkshire</p><br /><p>The second wave will start in January 2016 and we aim to announce details in November 2015. We are currently looking at the geographies and phasing for other areas and will aim to issue further information on this before the end of the year but in doing this we recognise that the position should remain fluid to take account of the views of local partners and also cases of failure.</p><br /><p>We expect all reviews to be completed by March 2017.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","13133","2015-10-29T17:46:20.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423217/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423217/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-22","Further Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many officials in his Department are working on the review of post-16 education and training institutions.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","13131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423218","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Department for Education (DfE) and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS), along with respective funding agencies, have re-prioritised staffing resources to support the review of post-16 education and training.</p><br /><p>There are seven reviews in the first wave of area reviews which have either launched since September or will launch in the next few weeks. Each review will take 3-4 months to complete and will be supported by resource from the DfE, BIS, Education Funding Agency and Skills Funding Agency.</p><br /><p>The area reviews of post 16 education and training are being undertaken in waves and can be triggered by either the local area requesting a review or the FE Commissioner or Sixth Form College Commissioner identifying the need for a review because one or more colleges in an area are at risk of failing. The first wave is underway now and details of the following reviews have been announced and can be found on the gov.uk website :</p><br /><p>Birmingham and Solihull</p><p>Greater Manchester</p><p>Sheffield City Region</p><p>Tees Valley</p><p>Sussex Coast</p><p>Solent</p><p>West Yorkshire</p><br /><p>The second wave will start in January 2016 and we aim to announce details in November 2015. We are currently looking at the geographies and phasing for other areas and will aim to issue further information on this before the end of the year but in doing this we recognise that the position should remain fluid to take account of the views of local partners and also cases of failure.</p><br /><p>We expect all reviews to be completed by March 2017.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","13131","2015-10-29T17:46:20.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423218/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423218/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-22","Further Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will publish the timetable setting out when each area will have its post-16 education and training reviewed.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","13133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423219","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-03","<p>Yes. The Joint Area Review Delivery Unit supporting the area reviews will advise Hon. Membersas a matter of course when reviews are due to be undertaken in any part of their constituency.</p><br /><p>Area reviews should take place as quickly as possible, the typical timescale being 3-4 months but this could vary depending on the number of colleges and complexity of the local issues involved.</p><br /><p>The reviews are aimed at delivering a skills system that meets the economic and educational needs of areas whilst also ensuring the long term sustainability of colleges to support productivity. Their purpose is not to secure savings to Government. However, early evidence from the pilot reviews indicates that there is potential for the reviews to secure efficiency savings.</p><br /><p>All applications to open a free school, academy, school sixth form or university technical college will be assessed on a case by case basis against the published criteria and taking account of local needs and circumstances.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","12977 ; 12978 ; 12979","2015-11-03T15:51:55.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423219/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423219/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-22","Further Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether hon. Members are always informed when a post-16 area-based review is announced for an area which includes their constituency.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","12976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423220","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-30","<p>The inclusion of investor-state dispute settlement (ISDS) provisions in the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) will not threaten the right of the UK or Devolved Administrations to regulate or determine public policy. The Commission has published a proposal for reforms to investment protections in this agreement, which includes a clause setting out governments’ right to regulate.</p><p>The UK will work with the Commission on this proposal to ensure that UK investors are treated fairly overseas by foreign governments while allowing governments to regulate lawfully and in the public interest.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-30T12:04:42.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423220/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423220/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-22","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of TTIP on different and separate regulatory systems for compliance with current ISDS provisions in different parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","12972"
