"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423233","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-27","<p>Liverpool City Council is forecast to collect £190 million in 2015/16, while for the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority Area the total forecast is £466 million. The 45 local authorities that comprise the North West are expected to collect £2,588 million in 2015/16.</p><p>The Government intends to move to 100% business rates retention for the local government sector across England by the end of this Parliament. As part of the new system, there will continue to be a redistribution of local tax revenue between authorities, with protections in place for authorities that might see their business rates income fall significantly. Over the coming months we will work with local government on the detail of these reforms.</p><br />","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-27T16:30:23.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423233/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423233/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-22","Non-domestic Rates: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the Government's proposed changes to business rates on (a) Liverpool Walton constituency, (b) Liverpool City Council, (c) the North West and (d) the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority area.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","13094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423234","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-30","<p>The lawfulness of the Aggregates Levy been challenged in the UK and European courts for over thirteen years by the British Aggregates Association. No court has ever found the levy to be unlawful.</p><br /><p>The legal challenges have also caused many years of uncertainty for industry, and have prevented the government from making any significant changes to the levy.</p><br /><p>The government’s legal costs are not finalised and are continuing to rise. This should be viewed against over £4 billion (and rising) in levy revenue that the government’s defence is protecting.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-30T14:22:12.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423234/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423234/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-22","Aggregates Levy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department has spent to date on legal fees in respect of the case against the Aggregates Levy brought by the British Aggregates Association.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","13069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423235","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-27","<p>Highways England will soon start a new programme of Route Strategies, aiming to develop an investment programme for the years 2020-25. These will be the forum where MPs and members of the public can make the case for improvements in their area. If improvements to the A595 are proposed through this process, they will be considered carefully for investment in the next Road Investment Strategy.</p><br /><p>Further details of Spending Review decisions will be announced on 25 November.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-27T16:17:08.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423235/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423235/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-22","A595","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy in the forthcoming Comprehensive Spending Review to provide ring fenced funding for a feasibility study into the trunk road section of the A595.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","13100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423236","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>I refer the member to the answer I provided on the 13 July 2015 to question 14259:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-07-08/6266/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-07-08/6266/</a></p><br />","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","12999","2015-10-29T14:55:51.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423236/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423236/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-22","Armed Forces: Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many serving members of each branch of the armed forces are in receipt of (a) child and (b) working tax credits.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","12998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423237","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>This is a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government.</p><br /><p>The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","12882 ; 13002 ; 13003 ; 13004","2015-10-29T15:05:34.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423237/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423237/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-22","Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment the Government has made of the effect on consumers of the practice of insurers in not giving details of no claims bonuses to customers in their renewal notice; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","13001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423238","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>This is a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government.</p><br /><p>The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","12882 ; 13001 ; 13003 ; 13004","2015-10-29T15:05:34.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423238/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423238/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-22","Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on consumers of the practice of insurers in automatically signing-up customers to annual policy renewals without their explicit consent; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","13002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423239","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-30","<p>As the Chancellor of the Exchequer has noted, the best outcome for the UK economy is that we achieve major economic reform of the EU. The Prime Minister is focused on success: he believes he can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU, and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis.</p><br /><p>The Confederation of British Industry and British Chambers of Commerce have both come out to say they support the reform agenda the Prime Minister is seeking to deliver.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-30T14:01:00.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423239/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423239/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-22","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the average net benefit per household of the UK's membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","12973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423240","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-27","<p>Last week the Chancellor of the Exchequer was in Manchester, Newcastle and Teesside and would hope to visit Cumbria in due course.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-27T16:13:11.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423240/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423240/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-22","Official Visits: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many official visits he has made to (a) Copeland constituency and (b) Cumbria as part of the Northern Powerhouse initiative.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","12937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423241","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-27","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer given by my rt. hon. Friend the Minister of State for Health (Alistair Burt) on 21 October, PQ 12272</p><p>In addition, a growing number of town and parish councils are involved in the delivery of work to support residents, in particular vulnerable elderly residents, through programmes such as village agent schemes, which can help older people feel more independent, secure, and cared for, and to have a better quality of life.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-27T16:31:58.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423241/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423241/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-22","Loneliness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of measures taken by local authorities in tackling loneliness; and what support the Government has provided for such measures.","false","Biography information for Mr John Baron","Basildon and Billericay","Mr John Baron","12940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423242","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-30","<p>The number of long term empty homes is at its lowest since records began. Over the last Parliament, the Government provided the right tools and incentives to tackle empty properties.</p><ul><li>Through the New Homes Bonus, local authorities earn the same financial reward for bringing an empty home back into use as building a new one. Since April 2011 almost £3.4 billion has been paid in recognition of the delivery of over 700,000 homes, plus over 100,000 long-term empty properties brought back into use. 75 per cent of local authorities are financially better off in 2014-15 than if New Homes Bonus scheme didn’t exist.</li><li>We made changes through the Local Government Finance Act 1992 so local authorities can charge up to 150% council tax for homes empty for over two years.</li><li>We extended permitted development rights to make it easier to convert property from business to residential to give new life to thousands of empty buildings.</li><li>We amended Empty Dwelling Management Orders to ensure they are only used to tackle the most problematic empty homes.</li><li>We provided £216 million direct funding to local authorities, registered providers and community groups between 2012- 2015 to help tackle the problem of empty homes and properties. This funding created 9,044 homes from empty properties.</li></ul>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","12962","2015-10-30T16:44:20.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423242/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423242/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-22","Empty Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what action the Government has taken to bring back into use long-term empty properties.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","12960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423243","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Government does not assess demand for housing or set housing targets. The National Planning Policy Framework and planning guidance expects local authorities to objectively identify and then meet the housing needs of their area.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-29T15:09:02.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423243/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423243/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-22","Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the number of properties required to meet housing demand in (a) England, (b) the North East and (c) Easington constituency in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","12961"
