ed within seven days.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","12953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423362","Home Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>In total, between 1 October 2014 and 30 September 2015 the National Crime Agency received 1,216 Suspicious Activity Reports under the provisions of the Terrorism Act 2000.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-10-29T17:30:57.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423362/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423362/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423362/answer/previousversion/25926","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Terrorism: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many occasions did the National Crime Agency received notice of suspicion of terrorist financing from private sector institutions, under Part III of the Terrorism Act 2000, in the last 12 months for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","12956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423363","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>In 2014-15 HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) issued 677 penalties to the total value of £768,000 across all the sectors it regulates. HMRC considers that releasing the number of investigations and visits made to businesses in different sectors could enable opportunists to identify where resource is being focussed, allowing criminals to arrange their activities accordingly to escape challenge. HMRC must protect information which could be used by criminals in this way and therefore is not able to release numbers on how many investigations are conducted in the Estate Agency Businesses (EAB) sector. HMRC took on supervision of Estate Agency Businesses under the Money Laundering Regulations 2007 from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) on 1 April 2014. Since becoming supervisor HMRC has used a range of interventions such as face to face visits, telephone interventions and webinars to reach hundreds of businesses in the EAB sector, and test and challenge their compliance with the Money Laundering Regulations. In addition to direct interventions, as supervisor, HMRC conducts risking work which involves using a range of sophisticated data exploitation tools - including their state-of-the-art Connect system - to identify cases which warrant further investigation. It is not possible to quantify how many businesses have been looked at in this way, as it is a routine aspect of supervision for HMRC. Where cases require criminal investigation, they are passed to HMRC's Fraud Investigation Service. HMRC is unable to disclose details of cases which are currently under criminal investigation for operational reasons.</p><p>I can confirm that estate agents that do not hold client money fall within the scope of the Money Laundering Regulations 2007.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","12787","2015-10-29T15:01:54.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423363/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423363/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-22","Estate Agents: Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether estate agents who hold no client money fall under the scope of the Money Laundering Regulations 2007.","true","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","12970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423364","Home Office","false","2015-11-03","<p>The Home Office does not hold data on the number of police within different forces who are suspended or are not on active duty as a result of investigation or complaint procedure.</p><p>From 2015/16, forces will be asked to provide returns that will include data on officer misconduct and whistle-blowing. This collection will include the number of recorded allegations of misconduct and gross misconduct; outcomes of disciplinary proceedings arising from those allegations; and the number of criminal investigations against those serving with the police. The Home Office intends to publish these data in due course once they are available.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-11-03T16:49:22.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423364/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423364/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Police: Disciplinary Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what data her Department holds on the number of police in different forces who are suspended or not on active duty as a result of investigations or complaint procedures.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","12926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423365","Home Office","false","2015-10-26","<p>No assessment has been made of the reasons for the recent reduction in the number of prosecutions for mobile telephone use while driving. Enforcement of this offence is an operational matter for the police. However, there may be a number of reasons, including drivers being more aware of the law, police deciding to prosecute drivers under more serious offences and officers choosing alternative methods of law enforcement, such as fixed penalties.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-10-26T17:50:16.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423365/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423365/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the reasons for the recent reduction in the number of prosecutions for mobile telephone use while driving.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","12927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423366","Home Office","false","2015-11-06","<p>I refer my Rt. Hon Friend to the answer I gave him on 27th October 2015 to question 12259.</p><p>It is the responsibility of the local Chief Constable, in conjunction with their Police and Crime Commissioner, to determine the resources they devote to tackling fraud and cyber crimes locally. The Government does not hold data on the proportion of calls received by Action Fraud which result in a police investigation.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-11-06T13:31:45.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423366/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423366/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Action Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of calls received by Action Fraud have resulted in a police investigation to date; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Damian Green","Ashford","Damian Green","12928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423367","Home Office","false","2015-11-03","<p>Work is under way across government to better understand the challenge from entryism. This will shape the plans for our review. I expect an initial report in 2016.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-03T17:18:18.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423367/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423367/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to paragraph 49 of her Department's Counter-Extremism Strategy, published on 19 October 2015, if she will publish the terms of reference of the review on entryism and specify what resources have ben allocated to that review.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","12969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423368","Home Office","false","2015-11-03","<p>We will publish the principles that will guide government engagement in due course.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-03T17:13:02.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423368/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423368/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will set out the timetable for publishing the principles referred to in paragraph 97 of her Department's Counter-Extremism Strategy published on 19 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","13033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423369","Home Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Home Office is working very closely with officials from the Office of the First Minister and the Deputy First Minister (OFMdFM) to assist Northern Ireland’s offer to welcome Syrians in need of help. At local level, the Home Office is represented in Northern Ireland at OFMdFM’s Syrian Refugee Strategic and Operational Planning Groups. We are also assisting OFMdFM officials in introducing the processes needed to enable the first intake of Syrian refugees to arrive in Northern Ireland.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-10-29T17:51:57.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423369/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423369/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress is being made to facilitate the arrival of Syrian refugees to Northern Ireland under the vulnerable persons relocation scheme.","false","Biography information for Dr Alasdair McDonnell","Belfast South","Dr Alasdair McDonnell","13036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423370","Home Office","false","2015-11-05","<p>We have engaged widely with partners, including across government, academia, faith groups and communities to develop our strategy.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-05T15:48:33.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423370/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423370/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which non-governmental groups and individuals her Department consulted on its Counter-Extremism Strategy, published on 19 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","13051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423371","Home Office","false","2015-10-28","<p>The Hon. Member’s question was answered on 22 October 2015.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-10-28T13:35:20.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423371/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423371/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Home Office: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she will Answer Question 11793 of 14 October 2015, on Home Office: staff.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","13040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423372","Home Office","false","2015-11-03","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring the integrity of the private security industry and this includes private investigators.</p><p>In July, the Government committed to a review (formerly triennial review) of the Security Industry Authority. That review may make further recommendations for legislative change which the Government will then consider.</p><p>Home Office Ministers have regular meetings with Ministerial colleagues and others as part of the process of policy development and delivery. As was the case with previous administrations, it is not the Government's practice to provide details of all such meetings.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-03T17:19:49.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423372/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423372/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Private Investigators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she expects provisions in the Private Security Industry Act 2001 on private investigators to come into force; which individuals and organisations she has held discussions with on these powers; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lord Garnier","Harborough","Sir Edward Garnier","13034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423373","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>We are determining the requirements and precise funding allocation for research to be commissioned. We will be working closely with a range of experts, including academics and universities, to improve our understanding of extremism. Opportunities for part-funded research will be allocated competitively.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-02T16:44:54.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423373/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423373/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Radicalism: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to paragraph 46 of her Department's Counter-Extremism Strategy, published on 19 October 2015, how much funding her Department will make available for commissioning and funding research.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","13049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423374","Home Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>We have taken the question to mean the credible commentators referred to in paragraph 65 of the Counter-Extremism Strategy. We are determining the requirements and precise funding allocation for research to be commissioned. We will be working closely with a range of experts, including academics and universities, to improve our understanding of extremism. Opportunities for part-funded research will be allocated competitively.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-04T16:58:29.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423374/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423374/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the criteria are for choosing the credible commentators referred to in paragraph 46 of her Department's Counter-Extremism Strategy, published on 19 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","13050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423375","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>Channel is a multi-agency process and support can be provided from a range of local agencies. The support programme is tailored to the individual based on an assessment of their vulnerabilities. It can include: ideological and theological mentoring; anger management; education skills; and family or health support. Further information is provided on page 17 of the Channel Duty Guidance, available on www.gov.uk.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-02T17:06:45.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423375/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423375/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to paragraph 88 of the Counter-Extremism Strategy, published on 19 October 2015, what support was given to the 700 individuals.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","13045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423376","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>The Extremism Community Trigger will be introduced in due course.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-02T17:07:52.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423376/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423376/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to paragraph 117 of the Counter-Extremism Strategy, published on 19 October 2015, what the timescale is for introducing the Extremism Community Trigger.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","13046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423377","Home Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>We continue to monitor and evaluate the Channel programme to ensure that it is as effective as it can be and that good practice is shared across the country. Channel evaluation is based on comprehensive monitoring systems which track outcomes over time and robust evaluation techniques that assess effectiveness.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-10-29T17:33:30.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423377/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423377/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what independent oversight arrangement has been established to monitor the Channel programme.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","13047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423378","Home Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>The Home Office intends to publish Channel data in the near future.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-04T17:00:20.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423378/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423378/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will provide information on the (a) age, (b) race, (c) gender, (d) religion and (e) region of residence of the 700 individuals referred to in paragraph 88 of her Department's Counter-Extremism Strategy, published on 19 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","13048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423379","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>The following individuals attended the first meeting of the Community Engagement Forum on 13 October 2015:</p><p>• David Cameron, Prime Minister</p><p>• Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon, Minister for Countering Extremism</p><p>• Theresa May, Home Secretary</p><p>• Louise Casey, Department for Communities and Local Government</p><p>• Max Chambers, Special Adviser on Home Affairs</p><p>• Camilla Cavendish, Number 10</p><p>• Brendan Threlfall, Number 10</p><p>• Arooj Shah, Councillor, St Mary’s Ward, Oldham</p><p>• Sean Harriss, Chief Executive, Lambeth Council</p><p>• Paul Martin, Chief Executive, Wandsworth Council</p><p>• Sheikh Musa Admani, Imam and Muslim chaplain, City University, London</p><p>• Fareed Ahmad, Ahmadiyya Muslim Association</p><p>• Farooq Aftab, General Secretary, Ahmadiyya Muslim Youth Association</p><p>• Michael Nazir-Ali, former Bishop of Rochester</p><p>• Khatun Sapnara, circuit judge • Aina Khan, solicitor</p><p>• Fiyaz Mughal OBE, Director, Faith Matters</p><p>• Sadja Mughal OBE, Director, Jan Trust</p><p>• Haras Rafiq, Managing Director, Quilliam Foundation</p><p>• Sara Khan, Co-founder and Director, Inspire</p><p>• Wahida Shaffi, Near Neighbours Coordinator; National Women’s Programme Lead, Christian Muslim Forum</p><p>• Faiza Vaid, Executive Director, Muslim Women’s Network</p><p>• Aysha and Kiran Iqbal Patel, Directors, Odara</p><p>• Kamal Hanif OBE, Executive Head, Waverley School, Birmingham</p><p>• Alun Francis, Principal and Chief Executive, Oldham College</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-02T17:14:53.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423379/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423379/answer","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423379/answer/previousversion/25930","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-22","Community Engagement Forum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 22 October 2015 to Written Question 11808, who attended the first meeting of the Community Engagement Forum, on 13 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","13090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423380","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Government have been clear in condemning the horrific attacks on religious communities by violent extremists including ISIL. All UK funded assistance is distributed on the basis of need to ensure civilians are not discriminated against on the grounds of race, religion, or ethnicity. We prioritise reaching the most vulnerable people across Syria, including Christians and those who have suffered from such violence. DFID continues to work with the UN and the international community to ensure all minorities’ rights are protected and our aid reaches those in greatest need.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-10-29T16:07:52.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423380/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423380/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-22","Syria: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to assist Christian refugees in Syria who are being persecuted.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","13013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423381","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-28","<p>As Secretary of State for International Development I led the UK delegation at the third International Conference on Financing for Development in Addis Ababa. In the run up to the conference, the UK Government undertook a programme of consultations on the FFD agenda with a range of stakeholders, including BOND, the UK membership body for organisations working in international development, whose members include Christian Aid and CAFOD.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-10-28T14:02:01.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423381/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423381/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-22","International Conference on Financing for Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, who represented the Government at the third International Conference on Financing for Development in Addis Ababa; and what steps the Government took to consult with NGOs, churches and other stakeholders on the UK's contribution in advance of that conference.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","12943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423382","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-29","<p>Access to justice is not just about proximity to a court. We are committed to providing alternatives to travel, for example through making better use of technology, including video conferencing, and exploring whether we can appropriately make use of civic buildings for certain types of hearing.</p><p>No decision has been taken to close any court. The consultation closed on 8 October and we are considering all responses carefully.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","12964","2015-10-29T14:43:44.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423382/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423382/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-22","Courts: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what account was taken of the effect on access to justice in rural areas in his Department's consultation on the Provision of the Court and Tribunal Estate.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","12963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423383","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-27","<p>For family court cases Ministry of Justice publishes quarterly figures on the number of disposals and the average time taken for their disposal by case type, and by the legal representation of the parties. The latest figures up to quarter 2 (April to June) 2015 can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/family-court-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/family-court-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2015</a></p><br /><p>Breaking down the parties representation figures for Wales nationally and for Gwent locally, private law disposals in Family Proceedings Courts and County Courts are as below:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Representation</p></td><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>Gwent</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Financial Year <br> 2013-14</p></td><td><p>Financial Year <br> 2013-14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Both</p></td><td><p>2,665</p></td><td><p>536</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>3,962</p></td><td><p>635</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>6,627</p></td><td><p>1,171</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr></tbody></table><br />","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2015-10-27T16:43:41.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423383/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423383/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-22","Family Proceedings: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many private family law cases there were in the (a) Gwent and (b) Wales civil and family tribunals cluster between April 2013 and April 2014; and in how many such cases both parties had legal representation.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","12954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423384","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-09","<p>Every self-inflicted death is a tragedy and we are committed to reducing the number of self-inflicted deaths in prisons.</p><p><br> All prisons are required to have procedures in place to identify, manage and support people who are at risk of harm to themselves, and the National Offender Management Service (NOMS) has put in place additional resources to undertake this safer custody work. NOMS is also reviewing the operation of the case management process for prisoners assessed as being at risk and the Government is considering the recommendations of Lord Harris’ Review into the deaths in custody of young adults.</p><p><br> HMP Liverpool is implementing the recommendations arising out of the most recent inspection by Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Prisons, published on 20 October 2015. The prison has a full safer custody team, which has been allocated additional resources to support prisoners identified as being at risk. It operates a Listener peer support service in partnership with the Samaritans and will shortly be opening an early days centre to improve support for new prisoners.</p><p><br> HMP Altcourse has a local safer custody improvement plan that includes improvements to the support offered to prisoners in their early days. It also operates a Listener scheme with the support of the Samaritans.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-11-09T13:06:51.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423384/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423384/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-22","Prisoners: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to support suicidal and vulnerable inmates in (a) HMP Liverpool and (b) HMP Altcourse.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","12986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423385","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-29","<p>Access to justice is not just about proximity to a court. We are committed to providing alternatives to travel, for example through making better use of technology, including video conferencing, and exploring whether we can appropriately make use of civic buildings for certain types of hearing.</p><p>No decision has been taken to close any court. The consultation closed on 8 October and we are considering all responses carefully.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","12963","2015-10-29T14:43:45.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423385/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423385/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-22","Courts: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to re-open court room provision in (a) Todmorden and (b) other rural areas.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","12964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423386","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-24","<p>It is for the Prime Minister to decide on the overall organisation of the executive. The implications of transferring responsibility for the Freedom of Information Act to the Cabinet Office were considered prior to this change taking effect. A formal impact assessment was not necessary.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2015-11-24T12:39:42.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423386/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423386/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-22","Ministry of Justice: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department conducted an (a) impact assessment and (b) internal review of the effect of the transfer of responsibility for freedom of information to the Cabinet Office prior to that transfer.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","13072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423387","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-27","<p>I refer the hon member to the Secretary of State’s statement of 13 October 2015. We have no plans to publish the overseas security and justice assistance (OSJA) guidance in relation to the bid to provide a training needs analysis to the Saudi Arabian prison service. No contract was entered into and the bid was withdrawn before the contract with the Saudi Government was signed.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-10-27T17:32:02.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423387/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423387/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-22","Prisons: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will publish the overseas security and justice assistance guidance that was issued before the Government entered into the contract to provide training needs analysis to the Saudi penal system.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","13078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423388","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-27","<p>Information relating to internal discussion and advice is not normally disclosed.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-10-27T12:01:35.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423388/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423388/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-22","Ministers: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Ministerial Code updated in October 2015, what discussions he has had with the Cabinet Office on the removal from that code of reference to Ministers complying with international law, treaty obligations and upholding the administration of justice.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","13073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423389","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-07","<p>a) I refer the Honourable member to the answer given to question 6553 on 15 July 2015.</p><p>b) The policy on books was implemented using existing resources.</p><p>c) I refer the Honourable member to the answer given to 12150 on 6 November 2015.</p><p>d) The cost of preparing the bid to provide a training needs analysis for the Saudi Arabian Prison Service was met from within the National Offender Management Service’s existing resources.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-12-07T16:12:14.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423389/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423389/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-22","Ministry of Justice: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the total cost to the public purse of his Department's proposed policies on (a) secure colleges, (b) the prisoners' book ban, (c) HMCTS privatisation and (d) Saudi prison contracts.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","13074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423390","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-19","<p>The Ministry of Justice does not collect information centrally on Litigants in Person in civil related court cases or family court cases.</p><br /><p>For both civil (non-family) and family court cases, quarterly figures are published broken down by legal representation. These can be found at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/civil-justice-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2015" target="_blank">http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/civil-justice-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2015</a>.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-11-19T17:16:16.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423390/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423390/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-22","Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, further to the Answer of 17 July 2013 to Question 163024, on Courts: Wales, what data his Department now centrally collates on litigants in person.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","13082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423391","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Governor and staff at Liverpool are determined to improve the prison and action is already being taken to address the recommendations made in the most recent report. We are working closely with Lancashire Care NHS Trust to improve the healthcare provisions. More prisoners are out of their cells in work, training or education, and a range of initiatives are also in hand to reduce violence.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-11-23T15:41:58.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423391/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423391/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-22","Liverpool Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to improve the (a) cleanliness, (b) degree of crowding and (c) safety of (i) prisoners and (ii) prison staff in HMP Liverpool.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","13092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423392","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-27","<p>NOMS does not tolerate violence of any kind in prison and any assault is treated extremely seriously. Any prisoner who commits an act of violence can expect to have action taken against them.</p><p>Statistics for assaults on staff by establishment are published in Table 3.15 of the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin. This can be found in the 'Assaults in prison custody 2000 to 2014' statistics at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-statistics</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-10-27T17:34:32.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423392/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423392/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-22","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many assaults on on-duty prison officers have occurred in (a) HM Prison Liverpool, (b) HM Prison Altcourse and (c) all other prisons in England and Wales in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","13109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423393","House of Commons Commission","false","2015-10-27","<p>This information was provided in a Written Statement made by my predecessor on 16 December 2014, cols 86–87WS:</p><p><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmhansrd/cm141216/wmstext/141216m0001.htm#14121636000008" target="_blank">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmhansrd/cm141216/wmstext/141216m0001.htm#14121636000008</a></p><p>The final cost of the Independent Options Appraisal was £2.02 million, excluding VAT.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2015-10-27T16:51:05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423393/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423393/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2015-10-22","Palace of Westminster: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, what progress has been made on confirming the final cost of the Options Appraisal Report into the refurbishment of the Palace of Westminster.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","13110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423394","Prime Minister","false","2015-10-29","<p>I have nothing further to add.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-10-29T15:03:41.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423394/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423394/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-10-22","Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, pursuant to the Answer of 21 October 2015 to Question 12154, for what reasons he did not refer to any legal basis in domestic law during (a) his oral statement of 4 September 2015, Official Report, column 23 and (b) the Answer of 14 September 2015 to Question 9571; and if he will describe the legal basis in domestic law used for the targeted killing of British citizens outside declared war zones; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","13070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423395","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-02","<p>We have a robust system in the UK for examining whether investments into our country are in the national interest. Safety and security in the civil nuclear industry are of paramount importance to the Government. Companies involved in the UK nuclear industry must do so in accordance with the UK’s stringent regulations enforced by an independent regulator. On this basis we welcome companies which can demonstrate the capability to contribute to safe and secure nuclear power generation in the UK.</p><br /><p>There is a longstanding convention of successive Governments not commenting in detail</p><p>on security and intelligence matters.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-11-02T15:40:58.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423395/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423395/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-22","China: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential threat to national security of the choice of the Chinese government company General Nuclear International as an investment partner for the development of the Hinkley Point C nuclear plant.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","13016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423396","Prime Minister","false","2015-10-29","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the position on the Wilson Doctrine set out by the Secretary of State for the Home Department, my right hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) during the debate on 19 October 2015, <em>Official Report</em>, column 700.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-10-29T15:02:15.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423396/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423396/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-10-22","Members: Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2015 to Question 8501, on the Wilson Doctrine, what responsibilities he has in relation to the operation of the Wilson Doctrine; what responsibilities the Home Secretary has in relation to that Doctrine; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","13009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423397","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>The lease for the Intercity 125 sets is a commercial matter between Great Western Railway (GWR) and the owner of the fleet. Under current plans, the transfer of the rolling stock is not conditional on Network Rail meeting its current regulated output targets on the Great Western Main Line electrification project.</p><br /><p>The planned schedule for the introduction of the InterCity Express Programme fleet to replace the Intercity 125 sets will see the new trains enter service from 2017 on the Great Western Main Line.</p><br />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-27T14:10:58.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423397/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423397/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","High Speed Trains","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the transfer of Intercity 125 sets from the Great Western franchise to the Scotrail franchise in 2017-18 is conditional on Network Rail meeting its current regulated output targets on the Great Western Main Line electrification project.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","13080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423398","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-30","<p>A reply was sent on 22 July 2015.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-30T12:19:40.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423398/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423398/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to respond to the letter from the Leader of Gateshead Council of 25 June 2015 on upgrading the A1 between the Birtley and Coal House interchanges.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","13042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423399","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>The table below details spend per head per region on cycling. These figures are made up of the following Government funded programmes: Cycle-Rail, Cycle Safety, Linking Communities, Cycle Ambition Cities, Cycle Ambition National Parks and the Local Sustainable Transport Fund.. The figures for total funding consist of DfT funding plus matched funding. Matched funding comes from a range of public and private sources, for example local authority budgets, private partnerships or third party grants.</p><br /><p>We do not hold a regional breakdown for the £4.8m spent in 2013/14 by the Highways Agency. The table also does not include the £11m a year spent on Bikeability cycle training, as we do not hold a regional breakdown of this funding. These funding streams have therefore been excluded from the below calculations. Further, as we are still in financial year 2015/16 we cannot confirm exact expenditure and we have therefore excluded the 2015/16 financial year from the figures.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Region</strong></p></td><td colspan="5"><p><strong>Average spend per head to nearest £</strong></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>North East</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>North West</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>South East</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>South West</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>Yorkshire &amp; Humber</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>13</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /> <br /><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-27T15:11:01.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423399/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423399/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 21 October to Question 12230, if he will provide a breakdown by English region of the figures provided in the first table contained in that Answer under the headings (a) his Department's spend per head and (b) total spend per head.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","13105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423400","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>This information is set out in the table below.</p><p>£ million</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Smartcard</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Automatic Vehicle Location</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>1.365</p></td><td><p>0.592</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>9.501</p></td><td><p>1.662</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>15.664</p></td><td><p>4.296</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>16.247</p></td><td><p>4.109</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>16.169</p></td><td><p>4.138</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Since 2010, these two supplements have helped lead to real benefits for passengers. Over 86% of buses in England outside London are now smart-equipped and 93% of buses outside London now have automatic vehicle location equipment compared to 45% in 2009-10.</p><br /><p>At this stage it is too early to estimate the likely payments for 2015/16.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-27T17:29:11.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423400/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423400/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 7 of his Department's publication, Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) Information pack and Conditions of Eligibility, how much his Department has spent on (a) the eight per cent ITSO smartcard BSOG supplement and (b) the two per cent Automatic Vehicle Location BSOG supplement in each year from 2010-11 to 2014-15; and what his Department's projected expenditure is in 2015-16 on those items.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","13102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423401","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>As the Department’s Permanent Secretary, Philip Rutnam, stated at the Public Accounts Committee of 21 October 2015, the estimate provided by Mr Carne has not yet been subject to detailed scrutiny, either by the Department or the Office of Road and Regulation(ORR). We expect to receive details of the estimate as part of the Hendy Review which will cover the entire 2014-2019 enhancements portfolio. This is expected later in the Autumn and it would be premature to comment on costs before the report is finalised.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-27T13:53:40.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423401/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423401/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Chief Executive of Network Rail's letter to the Chair of the Public Accounts Committee of 19 October 2015, what the component cost headings of Network Rail's revised £2.5 billion to £2.8 billion cost estimate for Great Western Main Line electrification are.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","13104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423402","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>Representatives from the following organisations attended the High Level Cycling Group’s meeting on 13 July 2015:</p><ul><li>Association of Train Operating Companies (ATOC)</li><li>Bicycle Association</li><li>British Cycling</li><li>Cyclists Touring Club (CTC)</li><li>Department for Transport</li><li>PTEG (Passenger Transport Executive Group) - Dialled in</li><li>Sustrans</li><li>The AA</li><li>Transport for Greater Manchester (TfGM) – Dialled in</li><li>Transport for London (TfL)</li></ul>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-27T13:46:45.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423402/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423402/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 21 October 2015 to Question 12187, which organisations were represented at the High Level Cycling Group's meeting on 13 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","13103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423403","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-30","<p>Since the introduction of the Continuous Insurance Enforcement (CIE) scheme, the level of uninsured driving has been reduced from 1.4 million vehicles at the end of 2010 to 1.0 million at the end of 2014, a 29% reduction. CIE has promoted positive changes in vehicle keeper behaviour and contributes significantly to making our roads safer and in helping keep down insurance premiums for the honest motorist.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-30T12:16:29.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423403/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423403/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment the Government has made of the financial effect on consumers of the requirement for drivers to be insured at all times under the Road Safety Act 2006.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","13000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423404","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-28","<p>The Secretary of State announced in June that Sir Peter Hendy, the new Chair of Network Rail, would develop proposals for how the rail upgrade programme, including the Great Western Mainline, will be carried out. He will report to the Secretary of State later in the autumn and it would be premature to speculate on his conclusions.</p><br />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-28T12:58:26.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423404/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423404/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans for the electrification of the Great Western Mainline to be completed.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","12958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423405","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-28","<p>Since 2013, and the setting up of Rail Executive Passenger Services, the Department has separated out the cost of individual Franchise Competitions and Direct Awards. Prior to 2013 such costs are merged within the general costs of running the franchised passenger services and we are unable to disaggregate them from the general costs.</p><br /><p>The cost of re-franchising projects since the re-launch of the Franchising Programme in Spring 2013 is £41.4 million. This represents the actual consultancy and non-pay staff costs for the duration of the completed competitions and Direct Awards. This figure includes costs for ongoing competitions and Direct Awards up to and including the end of September.</p><br /><p>Franchise competitions are not the result of negotiation, but of open competition. The benefits these competitions bring to the passenger far outweigh the cost to the Department. I also note that the franchising system returned £1.15billion to the taxpayer in financial years 2014/15, and is expected to return a similar amount in 2015/16.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-28T13:07:19.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423405/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423405/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been spent by his Department on franchising negotiations since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","12959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423406","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-28","<p>Network Rail was reclassified as an arm’s-length public sector body on 1 September 2014 and the collation of statistics of annual complaints received remains an operational matter for the company.</p><br /><p>Network Rail advises that its customer relationship management system focusses on providing solutions to a range of customer service requests, the majority of which are received from line-side residents rather than passengers. Network Rail’s system does not focus specifically on logging the annual number of passenger complaints.</p><br />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-28T12:55:12.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423406/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423406/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Railways: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many complaints by passengers were received by Network Rail in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013, (e) 2014 and (f) 2015.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","12957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423407","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-30","<p>Smart ticketing was taken forward by the Coalition Government after 2010. Five train operators, serving 73% of all rail season ticket holders in the South East, have now signed up to the South East Flexible Ticketing (SEFT) programme.</p><br /><p>Smart season tickets are already available to customers on Govia Thameslink Railway and c2c. South West Trains and Abellio Greater Anglia plan to introduce smart seasons on their services in January 2016; Southeastern will follow at the end of 2016.</p><br /><p>A new SEFT central back office, providing critical IT infrastructure and data processing capability, underwent testing in August 2015. This will enable train operators to consider a range of new products and services including automatic delay repay, flexible season tickets and loyalty schemes, and also to extend smart ticketing across a range of transport modes including rail, trams and buses.</p><br /><p>In September 2015, Birmingham New Street station reopened with smart-enabled ticket barriers supported by the central back office.</p><br /><p>On current plans, the South East Flexible Ticketing programme will complete in 2018.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-30T12:23:33.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423407/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423407/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Railways: Season Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans for the South East Flexible Ticketing scheme to be delivered.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","12942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423408","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>The Severn River Crossings concession is expected to end in the first half of 2018. At the end of the concession, the Severn Crossings will revert to public ownership.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-27T13:40:22.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423408/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423408/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-22","Severn River Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the Severn bridges to return to public ownership.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","12955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423409","Women and Equalities","false","2015-10-27","<p>Ireferthe Right Honourable Member to the answer I gave on 14 July to the written question below.</p><p><strong>Answer referred to</strong>:Civil Partnerships Act 2004: written question - 5833</p><p><strong>Tim Loughton:</strong>To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether she has any plans to bring forward an amendment to the Civil Partnerships Act 2004 to permit opposite sex civil partnerships.</p><p><strong>Caroline Dinenage:</strong>The Government has no plans to extend the Civil Partnership Act 2004 to opposite sex couples.</p><p>The Government carried out a review of the operation and future of the Civil Partnership Act 2004 required by The Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013, which included a full public consultation inviting views on potential changes to civil partnership.</p><p>The Government published a report, following the review, which concluded that the Government would not make any changes.</p><p>(14 July 2015 : written question 5833)</p><br />","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2015-10-27T16:34:03.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423409/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423409/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2015-10-22","Civil Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether plans to amend the Civil Partnership Act to allow opposite sex partnerships.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","13132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423410","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<p>DWP intends to exercise its right under the current contract to extend the service for a further 12 months. Commercial discussions are currently underway with the supplier.</p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-27T13:54:30.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423410/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423410/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-22","Vacancies: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he plans to continue the Universal Jobmatch service after the contract expires in April 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","13097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423411","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<p>We continuously review our employment programmes and consider global good practice examples.</p><br /><p>Many features of the Workforce Innovation and Opportunity Act are consistent with the current Work Programme framework and with Universal Credit which ensures work always pays and enables earnings tracking.</p><br /><p>We are considering how proposed improvements in the structure of US services could benefit UK employment support in the design of our future offers, for example our cross government look into supporting collaborations between services at a local level.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-27T14:08:16.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423411/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423411/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-22","Employment Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of lessons from the experience of the Workforce Innovation and Opportunity Act in the US to inform his plans to replace the Work Programme when the current contracts come to an end.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","13096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423412","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<p>Over five years 2010/2011 – 2014/15 the Health and Safety Executive has investigated 12,000 of 12,100 gas safety cases.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-27T13:50:48.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423412/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423412/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-22","Natural Gas: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of cases of complaints about gas safety are investigated by the HSE.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","13085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423413","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-30","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) have a clear policy on correcting errors where payments have been made to an incorrect bank account. This ensures that, where an error has been made, the intended recipient still receives the payments that they are entitled to. The Department also has clear procedures to recover funds paid to wrong accounts.</p><p>The procedures include establishing if the customer provided incorrect account details to the Department. If so, the account details are updated to protect further payments, but the claimant is asked to contact their bank for advice, as DWP had acted in accordance with their instructions.</p><p>Where official error led to an incorrect account being used then the missing payment is re-issued to the claimant using the correct account details. DWP then seeks recovery of the funds from the unintended recipient, either directly, where contact details are held on DWP’s systems or indirectly through a letter forwarded by the receiving bank, building society, or other institution, as appropriate.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-30T12:06:43.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423413/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423413/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-22","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what procedures his Department has in place to correct errors when benefits are paid into the wrong bank account.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","13052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423414","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<p>Sanctions that can be put in place by HSE range from verbal and written advice, improvement notices which require companies to take specified measures to achieve compliance and prohibition notices that stop companies from carrying out specified activities. Ultimately there is prosecution where unlimited fines are available in the Courts. (13083)</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-27T13:40:25.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423414/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423414/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-22","Natural Gas: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what sanctions the HSE can place on companies breaching gas safety.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","13083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423415","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<p><strong></strong></p><p>Over five years 2010/2011 – 2014/15 the Health and Safety Executive has (a) investigated 99.17% of cases; (b) with 1.38% (166 cases) having led to a prosecution. (13084)</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-27T13:44:28.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423415/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423415/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-22","Natural Gas: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of complaints about gas safety to the HSE are (a) validated and (b) prosecuted.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","13084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423416","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<br /><p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. A link to the impact assessment is included.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf</a></p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-27T16:50:54.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423416/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423416/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-22","Social Security Benefits: Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of proposals for a lower benefit cap on carers.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","13076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424403","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-28","<p>DFID is making important contributions to data availability, educational access and learning outcomes for children with disabilities in Kenya. The DFID-funded national special needs survey has collected comprehensive data on the educational needs of children with disabilities for the first time in Kenya; all new DFID infrastructure provide disabled access; and visually and hearing impaired children will soon be supported with learning materials.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-10-28T14:27:24.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424403/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424403/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-22","Kenya: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the projects her Department funds which help disabled children access education in Kenya.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","901844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424404","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-28","<p>Economic recovery has been slow. Delays setting up the National Reconstruction Authority and unrest in the border area with India, which has closed most border crossings for over 6 weeks, make economic recovery challenging. We are pressing the government to prioritise the post-disaster response.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-10-28T14:28:49.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424404/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424404/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-22","Nepal: Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the progress of the economic recovery in Nepal since the recent earthquake in that country.","false","Biography information for Lucy Allan","Telford","Lucy Allan","901847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424405","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-28","<p>There will be no substantive impact on existing DFID programming. It is right that we work with communities in the UK taking refugees as we do elsewhere in the world, but of course, we will stay within ODA rules.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-10-28T14:28:12.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424405/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424405/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-22","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect on her Department's work of re-allocating elements of her Department's budget to help local authorities deal with Syrian refugees.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","901845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424406","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-28","<p>The UK has been at the forefront of the response to the Syrian crisis. To date, we have committed over £1.1 billion. This makes us the second largest bilateral after the US and means we have done more than any other European country.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-10-28T14:29:24.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424406/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424406/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-22","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what progress the Government is making on meeting the UK's international obligations to refugees fleeing Syria.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","901850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424407","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-28","<p>In 2014/15, the Ministry of Defence provided fantastic support to DFID to support humanitarian activities, contributing £32million, and was therefore reimbursed from the ODA budget. This spending will count towards the target to spend 2 per cent of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) on defence.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-10-28T14:26:21.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424407/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/424407/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-22","Defence: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether any of her Department's spending will be counted towards the target of spending 2 per cent of gross national income on defence.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","901843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422789","Home Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>On 10 September 2015 a letter signed by 37 Bishops was sent to the Prime Minister. This letter set out how the Church stands ready to play their part but also how they believe the country could resettle more than 20,000 Syrian refugees over the next five years.</p><p>The Home Office wants to involve the Church in the design and implementation of the longer term programme of work. We are happy to have meetings with representatives from the Church to discuss the issues raised in the Bishops letter. Some of these meetings have already taken place with more planned over the next few weeks.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-09T11:53:46.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422789/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422789/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the Church of England following the letter sent to the Prime Minister by 86 bishops on 10 September about the Church providing funds to meet all additional costs of increasing the number of refugees taken into the United Kingdom; and what assessment they have made of the further support the Church of England can provide to meet the needs of refugees in the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422790","Home Office","false","2015-11-09","<p>The first 12 months of each refugee’s resettlement costs will be funded using ODA (Official Development Assistance). After year one we will also provide additional funding to assist with costs incurred in future years.</p><p>The anticipated cost for the first year is still being worked out between relevant Government departments and local authorities. We expect to agree indicative costings in the near future.</p><p>There are a range of factors that have to be included when it comes to bringing people to the UK and helping them to settle. Each person coming from Syria will have different needs so it is not possible to say how much the support for any individual will cost.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-09T11:52:15.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422790/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422790/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the cost, in the first year, of accepting Syrian refugees.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422791","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>We have updated our country information and guidance on Eritrea. This takes into account the UN Commission of Inquiry’s report as well other sources reporting on the human rights situation. The revised documents, covering illegal exit and national service, were published on 9 September and are available on the Gov.uk website. They recognise that there are human rights challenges in Eritrea – particularly around the national service programme – but, as with all asylum applications, stress the need to consider each claim on its individual merits.</p><p>All EU Member States have a responsibility to respect the principle of non-refoulement. We are confident that our European partners understand and apply this, whether to Eritrea or anywhere else. We are in regular discussions with our EU counterparts – individually and via the European Asylum Support Office – to discuss various aspects of asylum policy and practice.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2839","2015-11-02T15:54:41.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422791/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422791/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Refugees: Eritrea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will revise the country guidance for Eritrea so that asylum applicants from that country are favourably considered for protection as refugees, in the light of the Report of the Commission of Inquiry on Human Rights on Eritrea and other reports of human rights abuses in that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422792","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>We have updated our country information and guidance on Eritrea. This takes into account the UN Commission of Inquiry’s report as well other sources reporting on the human rights situation. The revised documents, covering illegal exit and national service, were published on 9 September and are available on the Gov.uk website. They recognise that there are human rights challenges in Eritrea – particularly around the national service programme – but, as with all asylum applications, stress the need to consider each claim on its individual merits.</p><p>All EU Member States have a responsibility to respect the principle of non-refoulement. We are confident that our European partners understand and apply this, whether to Eritrea or anywhere else. We are in regular discussions with our EU counterparts – individually and via the European Asylum Support Office – to discuss various aspects of asylum policy and practice.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2838","2015-11-02T15:54:41.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422792/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422792/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Refugees: Eritrea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to call upon all European Union member states to uphold the principle of non-refoulement for refugees from Eritrea.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422793","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>We remain concerned by reports of the use of torture in Mexico. Ministers have raised human rights with their Mexican counterparts on several occasions, including at the highest level during the President’s State Visit in March 2015. Officials at our Embassy in Mexico City also regularly raise our concerns in meetings with the Mexican government. In support of this ongoing dialogue, this year, the UK is working with the International Bar Association Human Rights Institute to train judges to deal with torture and enforced disappearance cases.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-11-04T15:38:30.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422793/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422793/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-21","Mexico: Torture","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Mexico following the publication in December 2014 of the report by the UN Special Rapporteur on Torture.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422794","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) have responsibility for negotiating the UK’s double taxation agreements, subject to oversight by HM Treasury. HMRC run an annual consultation exercise to establish the negotiating priorities for the coming year, which are then approved by ministers. As part of this exercise they consider representations made by UK businesses, NGOs and government departments, including the Department for International Development, as well as the UK’s diplomatic missions throughout the world. When the programme is published it also invites representations about our forward programme.</p><br /><p>HMRC’s programme for 2015/16 covers the following countries: Colombia, Fiji*, Ghana, Guernsey, India, Isle of Man, Israel, Jersey, Kazakhstan*, Kyrgyzstan, Lesotho*, Malawi*, Portugal*, Russia, Thailand*, Turkmenistan*, UAE*, US, Uruguay*.</p><br /><p>The UK’s starting point in negotiations is based closely on the OECD Model Double Taxation Convention, which is also the basis for most other countries’ tax treaties. Some developing countries prefer to follow the UN Model, the provisions of which differ in some areas to the OECD Model, and the UK has agreed to adopt these provisions in its treaties. The object of the negotiations is to produce a text acceptable to both countries, balancing their preferences. There is no timetable for how long negotiations should take. It is quite normal for negotiations to take two to three rounds to complete.</p><br /><p>Consultation during the negotiations would be rare.</p><br /><p>*Negotiations largely completed.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL2842 ; HL2843 ; HL2844","2015-11-04T13:56:08.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422794/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422794/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Double Taxation: Treaties","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government with which developing countries they are currently negotiating taxation treaties, and what is the timetable for each negotiation.","false","Biography information for Lord McConnell of Glenscorrodale",,"Lord McConnell of Glenscorrodale","HL2841"
