"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422798","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2015-10-29","<p>The last Executive Chef was employed by the House for just over a year. We paid £360to publicise the permanent vacancy in relevant forums. Reasonable travel expenses of several candidates were reimbursed at £83.40. An external consultant already engaged by Catering and Retail Services assisted with the selection process - a reasonable estimate of the cost of his time is £278. There were also marginal costs for the refreshment for the panel and ingredients to support a work-based skills test. The successful candidate had previously been employed on a fixed-term contract for which we paid an agency fee of £3,600.</p>",,"Lord Laming",,"2015-10-29T15:51:26.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422798/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422798/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2015-10-21","House of Lords: Catering","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees, further to the Written Answer by the Chairman of Committees on 18 September (HL2226), what costs were incurred in recruiting the last House of Lords Executive Chef, and for how long that postholder was employed.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL2845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422799","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-03","<p>Under international rules set by the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES), a hunting trophy from an endangered species can be exported only if the exporting country is satisfied that the hunt was both legal and sustainable in terms of its impact on the overall population of the species in that country.</p><br /><p>However, in the light of growing concerns about the sustainability of the hunting of some species, including lions, we have worked within the EU to introduce stricter controls on the import of hunting trophies of particular species. These require the importing country as well as the exporting country to consider the issue of sustainability. In this way the import of hunting trophies of certain species from certain countries is currently prohibited by the EU.</p><br /><p>We will continue to monitor the impact of trophy hunting and will work with the EU and our international partners to put in place greater protection, including prohibiting imports, if this is shown to be needed.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-11-03T12:57:03.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422799/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422799/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-21","Lions: Hunting","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their policy on legal imports of lion-hunting trophies into the European Union.","false","Biography information for Baroness Parminter",,"Baroness Parminter","HL2846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422800","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-02","<p>The information requested is not available for publication.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-11-02T14:28:55.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422800/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422800/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-21","Universal Credit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many families with three or more children born before 6 April 2017 they estimated would be affected by the proposed two-child limit for new claimants for Universal Credit in the calculations of the Budget policy costings for (1) 2017–18, (2) 2018–19, and (3) 2019–20.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL2847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422801","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-28","<p>We are aware of and seriously concerned by the cases of Dawood Hussein al-Marhoon and Abdullah Hasan al-Zaher. We have raised these cases at a senior level in the Government of Saudi Arabia, most recently on 11 October. The UK opposes the death penalty in all circumstances and in every country, especially in cases which do not meet the minimum standards defined by the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights. This includes the execution of a minor and the use of the death penalty for a crime which isn’t deemed “the most serious”.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-10-28T16:19:45.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422801/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422801/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-21","Saudi Arabia: Capital Punishment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Saudi Arabia concerning the cases of Dawood Hussein al-Marhoon and Abdullah Hasan al-Zaher.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL2848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422802","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>The review has not yet been completed. It is important that the issues identified by the review are properly tested with operational decision makers, so as to appropriately balance the protection of personal data and privacy with the public protection benefits and the operational need.</p><p>Due to the complexity of the operational and legal issues raised in the evidence gathering stage and the number of important stakeholders, this work is yet to be completed.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-02T15:57:47.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422802/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422802/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the review of the framework within which police forces use and retain custody images is yet complete; if so, what advice has been circulated to police forces as a result; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL2849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422803","Home Office","false","2015-11-05","<p>Following publication of the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration’s report last year and in consultation with key partners, UKVI produced and agreed an LGBTI ‘Action Plan’ to facilitate further improvements in the handling and management of asylum claims brought on the basis of sexual identity issues and to improve the training and guidance given to staff.</p><p>The key inspection recommendations have been reflected in this plan, specifically improving training and guidance to decision makers, improving claim recording mechanisms, ensuring policy compliance, and ensuring a consistent approach to explicit material and dealing with sexually explicit questioning. We continue to work with our partners in developing these strategies to ensure full implementation of the Chief Inspector’s recommendations.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-11-05T17:11:31.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422803/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422803/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Asylum: LGBT People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the action plan sent to the National Asylum Stakeholder Forum following the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration's report in 2014 on asylum on grounds of sexual orientation has now been agreed and implemented in full.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL2850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422804","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-04","<p>The majority of renewable electricity generation is supported by two government schemes; the Renewables Obligation (RO) and (for smaller schemes) the Feed-in-Tariff (FiT).</p><br /><p>Based on the number of Renewable Obligation Certificates (ROCs) awarded and the buy-out price for each ROC, the table below shows the amount of support provided by the RO for the years 2013/14 and 2014/15:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Payments made under the Renewables Obligation</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£ (million)</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wind turbines</p></td><td><p>1,791.9</p></td><td><p>1,866.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Solar photovoltaics</p></td><td><p>37.4</p></td><td><p>136.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hydro power generators</p></td><td><p>107.9</p></td><td><p>110.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>This information is available from the Ofgem website.</p><br /><p>The number of ROCs issued can be found in table 6.3 of the following link (copy attached):</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/energy-trends-section-6-renewables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/energy-trends-section-6-renewables</a></p><p><br> <br> <br> <br> <br></p><p>Payments made under the FiT scheme are not available by technology, but the majority of deployment is solar photovoltaic. In 2013/14, the total payments for the scheme were £691 million [1]. This is available from the Feed-in-Tariff annual report:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/sites/default/files/docs/2014/12/feed-in_tariff_fit_annual_report_2013_2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/sites/default/files/docs/2014/12/feed-in_tariff_fit_annual_report_2013_2014.pdf</a></p><br /><p>Annual generation statistics, irrespective of support mechanism are published in The Digest of UK Energy Statistics (DUKES). The table below summarises the generation figures for wind, hydro, and solar photovoltaic on a calendar year basis:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Generation (GWh)</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wind turbines</p></td><td><p>28,421</p></td><td><p>32,016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Solar photovoltaics</p></td><td><p>1,989</p></td><td><p>4,050</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hydro power generators</p></td><td><p>4,702</p></td><td><p>5,885</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Copies of DUKES are available from the House Libraries.</p><br /><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> The annual report for 2014/15 will be published in December 2015.</em></p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-11-04T16:47:45.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422804/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422804/answer","Number of ROCs issued.xls ; feed-in_tariff_fit_annual_report_2013_2014.pdf","Number of ROCs issued.xls ; feed-in_tariff_fit_annual_report_2013_2014.pdf","Number of ROCs issued ; FITs Annual Report 2013-14","Number of ROCs issued ; FITs Annual Report 2013-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422804/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-21","Renewable Energy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was their annual expenditure on financial grants, in the last year for which figures are available, for the installation of (1) wind turbines, (2) solar panels, and (3) hydro power generators; and what is their estimate of the total output of installations of each type.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL2851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422805","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-30","<p>The Department for Transport and the Low Carbon Vehicle Partnership established a Transport Energy Task Force in September 2014 to examine options to meet our renewable energy and greenhouse gas reduction targets, including through the wider deployment of sustainable biofuel. The Task Force included input from representatives of the Sustainable Aviation group. The Task Force’s report was published in March 2015 by the Low Carbon Vehicle Partnership. My hon Friend the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Transport, the Hon Member for Harrogate and Knaresborough (Andrew Jones) met with Task Force representatives, including Sustainable Aviation, in July.</p><br /><p>The Task Force recognised that sustainable biofuels have a valuable role in reducing carbon emissions from transport, particularly in sectors where there are limited alternatives such as aviation.</p><br /><p>We are assessing the benefits of making aviation biofuels eligible for certificates under the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO). We aim to include proposals in a public consultation next year on amendments to the RTFO scheme.</p><br /> <br />",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL2853","2015-10-30T10:33:36.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422805/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422805/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-21","Aviation: Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to including producers of aviation fuel in the Renewable Transport Fuels Obligation.","false","Biography information for Lord Soley",,"Lord Soley","HL2852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422806","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-30","<p>The Department for Transport and the Low Carbon Vehicle Partnership established a Transport Energy Task Force in September 2014 to examine options to meet our renewable energy and greenhouse gas reduction targets, including through the wider deployment of sustainable biofuel. The Task Force included input from representatives of the Sustainable Aviation group. The Task Force’s report was published in March 2015 by the Low Carbon Vehicle Partnership. My hon Friend the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Transport, the Hon Member for Harrogate and Knaresborough (Andrew Jones) met with Task Force representatives, including Sustainable Aviation, in July.</p><br /><p>The Task Force recognised that sustainable biofuels have a valuable role in reducing carbon emissions from transport, particularly in sectors where there are limited alternatives such as aviation.</p><br /><p>We are assessing the benefits of making aviation biofuels eligible for certificates under the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO). We aim to include proposals in a public consultation next year on amendments to the RTFO scheme.</p><br /> <br />",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL2852","2015-10-30T10:33:37.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422806/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422806/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-21","Aviation: Fuels","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to encourage the development of sustainable aviation fuels in the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Soley",,"Lord Soley","HL2853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422807","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-02","<p>The Government is supporting industry investment in the development and deployment of technologies for new aircraft, including technologies for new engines, aero structures and advanced systems, to reduce noise and other emissions from aviation.</p><br /><p>This support is integral to the work between industry and Government through the Aerospace Growth Partnership and the Aerospace Technology Institute (ATI), which published its Technology Strategy 2015 in July. To date, 100 ATI projects, worth around a total of £1bn, jointly funded by industry and government have been approved; and the majority of these are focused on technologies required to produce greener, more efficient and environmentally friendly aircraft.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-11-02T12:56:55.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422807/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422807/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Aviation: Noise","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to support research into new aircraft and engine technologies to reduce noise emissions from aviation.","false","Biography information for Lord Soley",,"Lord Soley","HL2854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422808","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-03","<p>In 2012 a National Noise Attitude Survey was carried out on behalf of the Department of the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs which included attitudes to noise from transport sources including aircraft.</p><br /><p>In 2014/15, Ipsos/MORI conducted on behalf of the Department for Transport a survey on noise attitudes which focused on noise from civil aviation, near to major airports in England. The results of the survey are currently being analysed with a view to publishing a report next year.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2015-11-03T12:53:16.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422808/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422808/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-21","Aviation: Noise","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what research they have conducted into (1) understanding how noise emissions from aviation impact on local communities, and (2) the effectiveness of different noise mitigation approaches in reducing the number of individuals affected by aircraft noises.","false","Biography information for Lord Soley",,"Lord Soley","HL2855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422809","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-03","<p>The UK has set targets for the next five years for air traffic management aimed at reducing flying times and therefore aircraft emissions. These are in line with the environmental target contained within the EU performance scheme. In addition UK industry is actively involved in the Single European Sky ATM Research (SESAR) programme which is developing new technology and operational procedures that will lead to further improvements in this area. This includes the implementation of the Civil Aviation Authority’s Future Airspace Strategy which has the need to reduce aviation emissions as a key objective.</p><p><strong></strong></p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2015-11-03T12:53:49.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422809/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422809/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-21","Aviation: Exhaust Emissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the potential to reduce aviation emissions through improved air traffic management.","false","Biography information for Lord Soley",,"Lord Soley","HL2856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422810","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-02","<p>The Government is supporting industry investment in the development and deployment of technologies for new aircraft, including technologies for new engines, aero structures and advanced systems, to reduce noise and other emissions from aviation.</p><br /><p>This support is integral to the work between industry and Government through the Aerospace Growth Partnership and the Aerospace Technology Institute (ATI), which published its Technology Strategy 2015 in July. To date, 100 ATI projects, worth around a total of £1bn, jointly funded by industry and government have been approved; and the majority of these are focused on technologies required to produce greener, more efficient and environmentally friendly aircraft.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-11-02T12:58:00.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422810/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422810/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Aviation: Exhaust Emissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to develop a supportive environment in the United Kingdom for the development and deployment of new aircraft and engine technologies in order to reduce emissions from aviation.","false","Biography information for Lord Soley",,"Lord Soley","HL2857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422811","Department for Education","false","2015-11-04","<p>The first financial year set up and running costs of the Regional Schools Commissioners (RSC) and their offices were approximately £4.5 million. This includes the election of head teacher boards and their expenses. This was not new additional funding, but was met from within the Department for Education’s existing budget envelope.</p><p>The budgeted running costs for 2015-16 are approximately £6 million. These costs have been provided from the department’s allocated funding, following a robust business planning exercise.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-11-04T17:02:47.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422811/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422811/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-10-21","Regional Schools Commissioners: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what were the costs set initially for the regional schools commissioners, and what are the budgeted running costs.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422812","Department for Education","false","2015-11-04","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw. I have asked him to write to you and a copy of his reply will be placed in the libraries of the House of Commons.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-11-04T16:33:57.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422812/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422812/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-10-21","Schools: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many schools were placed in special measures in (1) 2013–14, and (2) 2014–15.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422813","Home Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 (PACE) Codes of Practice set out the procedures that the police must follow in the exercise of their powers. The interviewing of suspects and witnesses is covered in paragraphs 11 and 12 of PACE Code C. In relation to interviewing pupils on school premises, I would refer you to paragraph 11.16 and Note for Guidance 11D:</p><p>11.16 Juveniles may only be interviewed at their place of education in exceptional circumstances and only when the principal or their nominee agrees. Every effort should be made to notify the parent(s) or other person responsible for the juvenile’s welfare and the appropriate adult, if this is a different person, that the police want to interview the juvenile and reasonable time should be allowed to enable the appropriate adult to be present at the interview.</p><p>If awaiting the appropriate adult would cause unreasonable delay, and unless the juvenile is suspected of an offence against the educational establishment, the principal or their nominee can act as the appropriate adult for the purposes of the interview. Note: Paragraph 1.5A extends the requirement in this paragraph to 17-year-old suspects. 11D Juveniles should not be arrested at their place of education unless this is unavoidable. When a juvenile is arrested at their place of education, the principal or their nominee must be informed. Paragraph 1.5A extends this Note to 17-year-old suspects.</p><p>In addition, Note for Guidance 2A in PACE Code G specifically relates to the investigation of the use of force by school staff. PACE Codes of Practice must be followed by all police officers in England and Wales. At a local level, police forces may provide their officers with additional guidance to that contained within the PACE codes. This guidance could relate to the protocols to be followed when interviewing pupils on school premises. Such guidance is not held centrally.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-10-29T17:07:38.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422813/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422813/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Schools: Police","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what protocols should be followed when a pupil is interviewed by the police on school premises.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422814","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-30","<p>The Law Commission has proposed extensive reform to the legislation around taxi and private regulation which requires careful consideration before recommending a way forward. We will share this the outcome of this consideration once it is completed.</p><br />",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-10-30T09:46:18.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422814/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422814/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-21","Taxis","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made on the Law Commission review of taxi and private hire cars, and rickshaws.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422815","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>The payment of a councillor’s legal costs by a local authority are subject to the same tax rules as the payment of such fees by any employer for an employee or office-holder. The tax treatment that applies will depend on the particular facts of the case.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-11-04T13:40:28.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422815/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422815/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Councillors: Legal Costs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the personal taxation requirements when a local authority pays the legal costs of an industrial tribunal or court case for an individual councillor.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422816","Department of Health","false","2015-11-02","<br /><p>This information is not collected centrally.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-11-02T16:56:27.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422816/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422816/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-21","Mental Patients","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many incidents requiring the attendance of the police occurred on mental health wards in the past 12 months; what were the ethnic, gender and age characteristics of the patients involved; and what was the ratio of staff to patients at the time of each incident.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422817","Home Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>Data is not recorded centrally on the number of individuals tasered who are detained under the Mental Health Act 1983 or on the monitoring of patients. A Taser record is completed by police officers on every occasion where a Taser is used. However, this record does not show whether individuals are detained or monitored after the incidents nor information on the ratio of staff to patients.</p><p>Police guidance specifies that all individuals who have been subjected to the discharge of a Taser should be examined by a forensic medical examiner.</p><p>To improve transparency around how force such as Taser is used by the police, the Home Secretary has asked Chief Constable David Shaw to carry out an in depth review of Taser data and other use of force. This will present options for collecting, collating and publishing data on how force including Taser is being used, who it is being used on and what the outcomes are.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2865","2015-10-29T17:10:07.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422817/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422817/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients: Stun Guns","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many patients detained under the Mental Health Act 1983 have been tasered in the past 12 months; what were the ethnicity, gender and age characteristics of the patients tasered; and what was the ratio of staff to patients at the time of each incident.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422818","Home Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>Data is not recorded centrally on the number of individuals tasered who are detained under the Mental Health Act 1983 or on the monitoring of patients. A Taser record is completed by police officers on every occasion where a Taser is used. However, this record does not show whether individuals are detained or monitored after the incidents nor information on the ratio of staff to patients.</p><p>Police guidance specifies that all individuals who have been subjected to the discharge of a Taser should be examined by a forensic medical examiner.</p><p>To improve transparency around how force such as Taser is used by the police, the Home Secretary has asked Chief Constable David Shaw to carry out an in depth review of Taser data and other use of force. This will present options for collecting, collating and publishing data on how force including Taser is being used, who it is being used on and what the outcomes are.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2864","2015-10-29T17:10:07.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422818/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422818/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients: Stun Guns","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what monitoring takes place of the use of tasers on patients detained under the Mental Health 1983, and how that monitoring information is made accessible to the public.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422819","Department of Health","false","2015-11-02","<p>The information is not collected in the format requested.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-11-02T16:47:44.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422819/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422819/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-21","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many patients are detained in medium and high security psychiatric hospitals; and how many such patients there are broken down by (1) ethnicity, (2) gender, (3) age, and (4) the length of time detained under the different segregated regimes.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422820","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-30","<p>The Government is currently assessing the risks and benefits of such harmonisation to inform its response to the public consultation and subsequent proposals.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-10-30T14:38:37.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422820/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422820/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-21","Digital Technology: EU Internal Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the European Commission's recommendation that spectrum should be harmonised and allocated across all 28 member states as part of the Digital Single Market.","false","Biography information for Lord Allen of Kensington",,"Lord Allen of Kensington","HL2867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422821","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-03","<p><strong></strong></p><p>The Mobile Infrastructure Project is being rolled out in Northern Ireland up to the end of March 2016.</p><br /><p>There are currently 7 masts in build phase. These are located in:</p><p>• Derry and Strabane District</p><p>• Fermanagh and Omagh (2 sites)</p><p>• Lisburn and Castlereagh</p><p>• Mid Ulster (3 sites)</p><br /><p>Planning permission was received for 4 sites. These sites are located in:</p><p>• Mid Ulster (3 sites)</p><p>• Newry, Mourne and Down</p><br /><p>Planning applications were submitted but decisions awaiting for 5 other sites. These are located in:</p><p>• Armagh, Banbridge and Craigavon</p><p>• Derry and Strabane District</p><p>• Fermanagh and Omagh (2 sites)</p><p>• Mid Ulster</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-11-03T16:53:10.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422821/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422821/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-21","Mobile Phones: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when and where the Mobile Infrastructure Project will be rolled out in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422822","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-04","<p>Children’s clothing, including a school uniform, is VAT zero-rated if it is designed for young children and is of a size that would fit the average child aged under 14 years. Larger sizes of clothing are standard rated irrespective of the age of the wearer.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-11-04T13:39:43.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422822/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422822/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Schools: Uniforms","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government under what circumstances value added tax can be applied to school uniforms.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422823","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>Hugo Shorter has been acting as Charge d’Affaires to Lebanon since 5 September.</p><p>We are currently seeking agrément for a substantive Ambassador from the Lebanese authorities. As soon as it is granted, a permanent appointment will be announced.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-11-02T14:29:55.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422823/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422823/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-21","Lebanon: Diplomatic Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect their new Ambassador to Lebanon to be in post.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422824","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-28","<p>The UK is committed to promoting stability and prosperity in Lebanon. We call on all parties to resolve the ongoing political deadlock, which is damaging the Lebanese government’s ability to provide its people with functioning state institutions and essential public services, including the supply of electricity. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) delivered this message in person when he spoke to the Lebanon’s Prime Minister during his visit to the country last month.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-10-28T16:20:14.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422824/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422824/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-21","Lebanon: Electricity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the government of Lebanon about practical ways in which the United Kingdom can help Lebanon to secure an uninterrupted supply of electricity.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422825","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-28","The British Government has been following Saudi Arabia’s counter-terrorism and terrorism financing legislation issue closely since it started being implemented on 31 January 2014. There has been no change to the limited level of religious freedom in Saudi Arabia and we are not aware of any persecution of religious groups through this legislation. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office continue to monitor this, including through the annual Human Rights and Democracy report.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-10-28T16:40:30.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422825/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422825/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-21","Saudi Arabia: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effect of Saudi Arabia's 2014 Penal Law for Crimes of Terrorism and its Financing on religious freedom in that country.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Coventry",,"The Lord Bishop of Coventry","HL2872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422826","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-28","The British Government strongly supports the right to freedom of religion or belief, which is restricted in Saudi Arabia. Saudi Arabia is a Muslim country in which Islamic law is strictly enforced and the public practice of any form of religion other than Islam is illegal. However, the Saudi authorities do accept foreign workers privately practising religions other than Islam. These restrictions on freedom of religion or belief reflect widely-held conservative social values in Saudi society. The Saudi authorities are encouraging reforms but at a pace that is acceptable to its society.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-10-28T16:41:13.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422826/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422826/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-21","Saudi Arabia: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the freedom of religious minorities in Saudi Arabia to practise their religion or belief in private.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Coventry",,"The Lord Bishop of Coventry","HL2873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422827","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>The British Government has not provided support, financial or otherwise, to the King Adbdullah Bin Abdulaziz International Centre for Interreligious and Intercultural Dialogue in Vienna.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-11-04T13:56:38.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422827/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422827/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-21","King Abdullah Bin Abdulaziz International Centre for Interreligious and Intercultural Dialogue","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what support, financial or otherwise, they have provided to the King Adbdullah Bin Abdulaziz International Centre for Interreligious and Intercultural Dialogue in Vienna.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Coventry",,"The Lord Bishop of Coventry","HL2874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422828","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-03","<p>We recognise the importance of early payments to the rural community. As at 22 October, Environmental Stewardship advance payments had been made to 25,200 agreement holders with a total value of £62.5 million. Natural England and the Rural Payments Agency continue to work to get payments out as soon as possible with the aim of making the remaining advance payments in November and December.</p><br /><p>This year, 2015, has been a transitional year as new Common Agricultural Policy rules have taken effect. Whilst we would expect these payments to start earlier next year, from 2018 new EU rules will prevent any payments being made before 16 October.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-11-03T12:54:26.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422828/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422828/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-21","Agriculture: Subsidies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to have fulfilled the agri-environment scheme payments to farmers, and how they will ensure that delays in making such payments do not happen next year.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL2875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422829","Cabinet Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>As set out in legislation, each candidate at an ordinary Police and Crime Commissioner election is entitled to have an election address published on a website dedicated to promoting the candidates for these polls, and an elector can request a printed version of the election addresses for the police area where they are entitled to vote to be sent to them.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-11-04T17:30:18.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422829/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422829/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-21","Police and Crime Commissioners: Election Addresses","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have plans to make available free postal delivery to every elector of every candidate's election communication in the forthcoming Police and Crime Commissioner elections.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422830","Department of Health","false","2015-11-02","<p>The use of antifungal medication is not licensed for the treatment of patients with Alzheimer's disease. Consequently there would be no requirement for systematic monitoring of the use of these drugs.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-11-02T17:05:17.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422830/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422830/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-21","Alzheimer's Disease: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will ask general practitioners who prescribe antifungals to patients with Alzheimer's disease to notify the National Health Service of the results of that treatment, in the light of the article published online by <i>Nature </i>on 15 October regarding the infection of different brain regions with fungi in Alzheimer's.","false","Biography information for Lord Lucas",,"Lord Lucas","HL2877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422831","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-10-28","<p>The publication of information relating to determinations made by the Parades Commission for Northern Ireland is an operational matter for the Commission acting independently of Government.</p><br />",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2015-10-28T15:18:19.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422831/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422831/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-10-21","Parades Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will require the Northern Ireland Parades Commission to publish information relating to each determination it makes, and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL2878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422832","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Government remains fully committed to supporting the institutions and principles established under the Belfast Agreement.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2015-10-29T15:35:36.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422832/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422832/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-10-21","Northern Ireland Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will take steps to ensure that all decisions about names of areas in Northern Ireland must be taken by mutual agreement of the two communities, as outlined in the 1998 Belfast Agreement.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL2879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422833","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>The National Ugly Mugs Scheme is a mechanism for reporting crimes committed against people involved in prostitution. The Home Office provided £108,000 for the pilot scheme that ran from April 2012 to March 2013, coordinated by the UK Network of Sex Worker Projects. The evaluation of the pilot is available on its website.</p><p>The previous Government supported the pilot as part of its drive to end violence against women and girls. This Government is pleased that the evaluation of the scheme shows that it was successful in increasing access to justice and protection for those involved in prostitution. Police forces have been encouraged to contribute financially to the scheme, given its crime prevention focus and its role in encouraging reporting and contributing to intelligence. That is a decision for individual forces, and the Home Office does not collect information regarding which forces have contributed.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2881","2015-11-02T17:17:37.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422833/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422833/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Prostitution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what benefits they found resulted from the national Ugly Mugs Scheme piloted by the Home Office; whether it was assessed as good value for money; and if so, what was the result.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL2880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422834","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>The National Ugly Mugs Scheme is a mechanism for reporting crimes committed against people involved in prostitution. The Home Office provided £108,000 for the pilot scheme that ran from April 2012 to March 2013, coordinated by the UK Network of Sex Worker Projects. The evaluation of the pilot is available on its website.</p><p>The previous Government supported the pilot as part of its drive to end violence against women and girls. This Government is pleased that the evaluation of the scheme shows that it was successful in increasing access to justice and protection for those involved in prostitution. Police forces have been encouraged to contribute financially to the scheme, given its crime prevention focus and its role in encouraging reporting and contributing to intelligence. That is a decision for individual forces, and the Home Office does not collect information regarding which forces have contributed.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2880","2015-11-02T17:17:37.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422834/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422834/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-21","Prostitution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which police forces contributed to the national Ugly Mugs Scheme during 2014–15.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL2881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422837","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Government recognises that energy costs are among the factors that have an impact on the competitiveness of the steel industry and for that reason has provided over £50 million compensation to steel makers for energy costs.</p><p>We are also in advanced discussions with the European Commission to approve millions of pounds of further compensation for energy intensive industries, including steel makers. Many years of underinvestment in the UK’s energy infrastructure has meant wholesale prices of energy are higher in the UK than in some other EU countries. The Government is committed to addressing this long term issue through, for example, new nuclear plants and our support for shale gas extraction.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-29T15:26:57.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422837/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422837/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Iron and Steel: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the level of energy prices on the steel industry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","12722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422838","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>This is a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government.</p><br /><p>The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-26T15:30:55.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422838/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422838/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Insurance: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of whether insurers are increasing their premiums year on year due to the automatic renewal of policies without customers' explicit consent.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","12727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422839","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-29","<p>The number of Apprenticeship Starts on Standards (known previously as Trailblazers) is published as part of the Department’s Statistical First Release (first link). Table 20.1 (second link) shows the provisional number of starts on Standards in the 2014/15 academic year, by quarter.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-held" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-held</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468260/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-data-tables-october15-ofqual-update.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468260/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-data-tables-october15-ofqual-update.xls</a></p><p>Provisional data for August to October 2015 will be published in January 2016.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-29T17:08:29.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422839/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422839/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many apprenticeships have been created under the Trailblazer scheme in the last nine months.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Mr Henry Bellingham","12763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422840","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-27","<p>The Perkins Review of engineering skills made it clear that boosting the number engineers was not an agenda that Government could tackle alone. Engineering employers, the profession and educators should work together with Government to increase the supply of engineers in the UK.</p><br /><p>Government published a one year on progress report in November 2014. This summarised all the actions taken by Government and the engineering community (led by RAEng) in response to the review. This can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/369566/bis-14-1164-engineering-skills-perkins-review-progress-report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/369566/bis-14-1164-engineering-skills-perkins-review-progress-report.pdf</a></p><br /><p>Government interventions include:</p><br /><p>Inspiring young people to consider engineering careers through the Tomorrow’s Engineers week, STEM ambassadors in schools and improved careers advice. We are reforming the curriculum to support science and innovation with more rigorous science GCSEs, new Science A levels, Tech Level and Technical Baccalaureate qualifications and more University Technical Colleges specialising in technical and scientific subjects.</p><br /><p>We are committed to 3m apprenticeship starts this parliament and many of the new employer-led trailblazer apprenticeships standards are in the engineering and manufacturing sector. We are rolling out more degree and higher level apprenticeships to deliver the high level technical skills employers need. We have introduced National Colleges to provide high level skills in sectors crucial for the economy.</p><br /><p>We have invested in higher education for STEM teaching facilities (£200m) and the teaching of high cost subject such as engineering (£185m).</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-27T17:06:03.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422840/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422840/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Engineering Skills Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what progress he has made in implementing professor John Perkins' Review of Engineering Skills published by his Department in November 2013.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","12911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422841","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-28","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills spoke with Competition Commissioner Verstager on Friday 23 October, to raise the issue of state aid clearance for our proposed package of support for energy intensive industries. Further discussions are planned this week, and next month. In addition, my officials have been in regular contact with the European Commission throughout this process, and have met with the Commission’s case handler to help progress clearance of the support package.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","12654","2015-10-28T17:44:27.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422841/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422841/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Iron and Steel: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to encourage the European Commission to have measures approved to support UK steelmakers with their energy costs.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","12870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422842","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-03","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has received a few representations, mainly on behalf of the ‘Keep Me Posted Campaign’, (and nine from hon. Members in 2014 on behalf of their constituents) which have included reference to the desire for paper bills to be supplied free of charge.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-11-03T15:24:01.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422842/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422842/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Billing: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations his Department has received about customers without internet access being charged to receive paper bills.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","12871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422843","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-27","<p>The Government encourages all employers to pay more than the National Minimum Wage and the National Living Wage where they can afford to. The Low Pay Commission’s remit is to set the National Minimum Wage as high as possible without harming employment prospects.</p><br /><p>According to Office for Budget Responsibility estimates, the National Living Wage will benefit 2.7 million low wage workers by 2020. The increase in April 2016 to £7.20 from the current NMW of £6.70 will mean a 7.5% increase in hourly pay, and a full time worker will earn £910 more per annum compared to today.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-27T17:04:52.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422843/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422843/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Living Wage: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to encourage employers in London to pay the London Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","12895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422844","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-26","<br /><p>The latest statistics available from the Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) show that in the academic year 2013/14 there were 1.1 million UK domiciled enrolments at UK Higher Education Institutions, of which 138,670 declared a disability.</p><br /><p>Further information is published on the HESA website and can be located from this web-link <a href="https://www.hesa.ac.uk/content/view/1973/239/" target="_blank">https://www.hesa.ac.uk/content/view/1973/239/</a></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-26T15:27:33.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422844/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422844/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Students: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of the number of students with a disability in higher education; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","12896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422845","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-26","<br /><p>Disabled Students’ Allowances are available to help meet the additional costs that a disabled student is obliged to incur, in relation to their study, by virtue of their disability.</p><br /><p>Disabled Students’ Allowances, along with all other types of student support, are reviewed before laying the annual student support regulations.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-26T15:26:07.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422845/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422845/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Students: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department has reviewed the adequacy of financial support for students with disabilities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","12897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422846","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-27","<p>There is a longstanding principle, dating back to 2005, which was communicated to the sector in the 2007/08 funding year, that, in general, we do not provide funding for provision that is either an employer or a statutory requirement. Instead, we believe that these costs should be met by employers or individuals themselves.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-27T17:03:31.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422846/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422846/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he took the decision not to provide funding to trainees to support the cost of gaining a large goods vehicle licence.","true","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","12925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422847","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-28","<p>The Licensing Act 2003 (which is the responsibility of my Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for the Home Department) sets out the types of regulated entertainment that require a licence, primarily live music and indoor sporting events. Any requirements in the 2003 Act are separate to any requirement around public liability insurance to be in place. Any requirements on public liability insurance is a contractual matter and is not required by law.</p><p>Guidance for organisers of events has been produced by the Cabinet Office and can be seen on<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/can-do-guide-for-organisers-of-voluntary-events/the-can-do-guide-to-organising-and-running-voluntary-and-community-events#part-6-do-i-need-insurance" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>. This includes the following relating to insurance:</p><p>There is no law that says you must buy insurance for a voluntary or community event – but you might want to make sure you are covered in case something goes wrong and someone makes a claim against you. Having<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/can-do-guide-for-organisers-of-voluntary-events/the-can-do-guide-to-organising-and-running-voluntary-and-community-events#what_is_public" target="_blank">public liability insurance</a>may give you peace of mind, but it’s good planning, not insurance that stops things going wrong.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-10-28T17:46:16.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422847/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422847/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-21","Entertainments: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the requirements are on places of public entertainment to have public liability insurance in place; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","12904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422848","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-28","<p>Section 39 of the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-Party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014 provides for a post-election review of the operation of the regulatory regime governing third parties at the 2015 General Election.</p><p>Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts CBE is currently conducting this independent review.</p><p>Ministers must lay a copy of his report before Parliament and publish it by November 2016.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","12774","2015-10-28T15:12:29.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422848/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422848/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-21","Transparency of Lobbying, Non-party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment his Department has made of the effects of the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-Party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014 on the activities of trades unions during the 2015 general election period.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin John Docherty","12773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422849","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-28","<p>Section 39 of the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-Party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014 provides for a post-election review of the operation of the regulatory regime governing third parties at the 2015 General Election.</p><p>Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts CBE is currently conducting this independent review.</p><p>Ministers must lay a copy of his report before Parliament and publish it by November 2016.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","12773","2015-10-28T15:12:29.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422849/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422849/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-21","Transparency of Lobbying, Non-party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment his Department has made of the effects of the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-Party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014 on the activities of charitable bodies during the 2015 general election period.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin John Docherty","12774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422850","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-26","<p>Work on the Strategic Defence and Security Review is progressing well and we expect it to be published by the end of the year. During the course of the review we have engaged with a wide range of stakeholders and external experts including Parliamentarians, academics, think tanks, NGOs, industry and international allies. Members of the public also have the opportunity to contribute views via a dedicated page on gov.uk.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2015-10-26T14:04:11.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422850/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422850/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-21","Strategic Defence and Security Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent progress his Department has made on the Strategic Defence and Security Review.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","12796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422851","Department of Health","false","2015-10-29","<p>There is no plan to launch an independent inquiry into the sustainability of the National Health Service and there will therefore be no consequential effects on the devolved administrations or adverse effects to the Scottish block grant.</p><br /><p>The Government remains committed to the principles of the NHS, enshrined in the NHS Constitution and in working with the NHS in implementing its own plan for the future of the NHS – the Five Year Forward View. By 2020-21, the Government will increase funding for the NHS by £10 billion a year in real terms compared to 2014-15 to support the transformation of services across the country.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-10-29T17:18:22.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422851/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422851/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-21","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for NHS Productivity of 9 July 2015, Official Report, House of Lords, column 286, on proposals for an independent inquiry on the sustainability of the NHS, if he will take steps to ensure that any such inquiry (a) identifies possible consequential effects and (b) does not adversely affect the Scottish block grant.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","12745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422852","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>The Government is making changes to Tax Credits which will help put welfare spending on a more sustainable path. The Government wants to move from a low wage, high tax, high welfare society to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society.</p><br /><p>Alongside the introduction of the New Living Wage and raising the Personal Allowance, the intended impact of these reforms is to incentivise work, ensure work always pays, and then allow people to keep more of what they earn.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-26T15:39:06.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422852/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422852/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Working Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of (a) the reduction in the level at which working tax credit begins to be withdrawn from £6,420 to £3,850 from April 2015 on work incentives for those on low incomes and (b) increasing of the taper rate to 48 per cent on work incentives for those on low incomes.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","12725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422853","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-05","<p>The Government is supporting household incomes by introducing a new National Living Wage (NLW) for workers aged 25 and above from April 2016. The NLW will be introduced at a level of £7.20, 50p more than the current NMW which means a £900 p.a. increase in earnings next year for a full-time worker. By 2020 the NLW is expected to be over £9 an hour, meaning a full-time worker will earn £4,800 more than today.</p><br /><p>By 2020 it is expected that the NLW will directly benefit 2¾m workers; while up to 6m could benefit from ripple effect. A number of large employers have already started paying wages at or above the NLW level, these include Ikea, Lidl, and Morrisons.</p><br />","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-11-05T15:12:29.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422853/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422853/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Personal Income","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of the reduction in household income arising from net tax and benefit reforms in the Summer Budget 2015 will be made up by an increase in household income arising from the new National Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","12726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422854","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs is able to support customers who need additional help such as taking applications by phone.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-26T15:36:02.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422854/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422854/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Married People: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to support non-online applications for marriage allowance by couples on low incomes.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","12791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422855","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>The information requested is not available. The Summer Budget offered a new deal for working people. It means Britain moving from a high welfare, high tax, low wage economy to a lower welfare, lower tax, higher wage society.</p><br /><p>A new National Living Wage for workers aged 25 and above, initially set at £7.20 per hour from April 2016, will directly benefit 2.7 million low wage workers, and up to 6 million could see a pay rise as a result of a ripple effect up the earnings distribution. The new National Living Wage will boost pay for those currently earning the National Minimum Wage by £4,800 a year by 2020 when the National Living Wage is expected to rise to over £9 per hour.</p><br /><p>To help working families keep more of what they earn, the personal allowance will increase to £11,000 in 2016-17 and £11,200 in 2017-18. The government has committed to increase the personal allowance to £12,500 by 2020 which will mean that a typical basic rate taxpayer will see their income tax cut by £1,205 a year compared to 2010.</p><br /><p>An illustrative renting family with two children, where one parent works full-time on the minimum wage, will be over £2,400 better off in cash terms by 2020.</p><br /><p>The government set out its assessment of the impacts of the Summer Budget policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20<sup>th</sup> July 2015. Taken together, the introduction of the National Living Wage, increases in the personal allowance and welfare changes mean that 8 out of 10 working households will be better off as a result of the Summer Budget.</p><br /><p>In response to a request from the Secondary Legislation Scrutiny Committee, the government has chosen to produce and release an impact assessment on the tax credit changes to the Committee. The impact assessment shows that 60% of the tax credit savings come from the half of tax credit claimants with the highest income.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-26T17:47:26.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422855/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422855/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Working Tax Credit: Peterborough","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many and what proportion of recipients of working tax credits in Peterborough constituency are citizens of non-UK EU member states; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","12792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422856","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-02","<p>At the Summer Budget the government announced the creation of a Roads Fund so that from 2020 all money raised from VED in England will be invested in the Roads Fund and used to improve the English strategic road network. The latest figures for VED revenue can be found in Table C.3 of Summer Budget 2015, which can be found here <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summer-budget-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summer-budget-2015</a>. Revenue raised for previous years can be found in the relevant Budget document.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","12806 ; 12835","2015-11-02T16:40:05.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422856/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422856/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will allocate a proportion of road tax receipts to the repair of roads.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","12805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422857","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-02","<p>At the Summer Budget the government announced the creation of a Roads Fund so that from 2020 all money raised from VED in England will be invested in the Roads Fund and used to improve the English strategic road network. The latest figures for VED revenue can be found in Table C.3 of Summer Budget 2015, which can be found here <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summer-budget-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summer-budget-2015</a>. Revenue raised for previous years can be found in the relevant Budget document.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","12805 ; 12835","2015-11-02T16:40:05.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422857/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422857/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Fuels: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will allocate a proportion of fuel duty receipts to the repair of roads.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","12806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422858","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-27","<p>Treasury Ministers are in regular contact with Welsh Government Ministers on a variety of matters.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-27T16:03:15.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422858/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422858/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received from the Welsh Government on the Barnett consequentials for Wales resulting from public expenditure on High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","12781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422859","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>The government does not expect the restriction to tax relief for finance costs to have a significant impact on small investors, with only 1 in 5 landlords affected. Overall, the OBR believe the impact on the housing market will be small and, taking account of the other measures in the Summer Budget, have not adjusted their forecast for house prices. The Productivity Plan published alongside the Summer Budget will also increase the number of opportunities available to small investors. It includes a number of measures to make the planning system quicker, cheaper and more responsive to local needs.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-29T17:55:15.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422859/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422859/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Private Rented Housing: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on small investors of planned restrictions on the relief on finance costs for landlords of residential property.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart McDonald","12733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422860","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>The Financial Policy Committee (FPC) assess the impact of the Help to Buy: mortgage guarantee scheme on an annual basis. The most recent review was carried out by the FPC in September 2015. The FPC’s view was that the scheme has not been a material driver of house price growth.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-26T15:32:37.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422860/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422860/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Housing: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his most recent assessment is of the effect of the Help to Buy scheme on house prices.","false","Biography information for George Kerevan","East Lothian","George Kerevan","12754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422861","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>The Treasury continuously monitors global economic developments, including Japanese inflation developments, and their impact on the UK as part of the normal process of policy development.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-26T15:26:23.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422861/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422861/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Economic Situation: Japan","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will assess the potential effects of the Japanese deflation on the UK economy.","false","Biography information for George Kerevan","East Lothian","George Kerevan","12755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422862","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-28","<p>The Government is reducing Corporation Tax to 19% from 2017-18 and then to 18% from 2020-21; setting the Annual Investment Allowance at a new permanent level of £200,000; and increasing the Employment Allowance by £1,000 to £3,000 from 2016-17. The increase in the employment allowance means a business could employ four people on the National Living Wage and pay no National Insurance Contributions.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-28T15:43:02.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422862/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422862/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-21","Small Businesses: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will bring forward proposals to assist SMEs with higher labour costs by 2020 under the National Living Wage.","false","Biography information for George Kerevan","East Lothian","George Kerevan","12756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422863","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-09","<p>In the last two financial years HM Treasury has received £1.3bn in LIBOR and FX banks fines. All LIBOR penalties received in this time period have been allocated to military or other uniformed charities. All foreign exchange penalties received in this time period have been allocated to create a fund for advanced care in GP practices and community healthcare facilities.</p><br /><p>Each bid for charitable funding from Libor fines is considered on its individual merits and with a clear intention that awards should benefit the widest range of military charities and good causes across the whole of the United Kingdom.</p><br /><p>Awards of Libor funds are usually made at the Autumn Statement or the Budget.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","12743 ; 12826 ; 12827","2015-11-09T14:39:47.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422863/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422863/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","LIBOR: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much of the funding raised from Libor fines has been distributed to charitable projects and good causes in each region and constituent part of the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","12742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422864","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-09","<p>In the last two financial years HM Treasury has received £1.3bn in LIBOR and FX banks fines. All LIBOR penalties received in this time period have been allocated to military or other uniformed charities. All foreign exchange penalties received in this time period have been allocated to create a fund for advanced care in GP practices and community healthcare facilities.</p><br /><p>Each bid for charitable funding from Libor fines is considered on its individual merits and with a clear intention that awards should benefit the widest range of military charities and good causes across the whole of the United Kingdom.</p><br /><p>Awards of Libor funds are usually made at the Autumn Statement or the Budget.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","12742 ; 12826 ; 12827","2015-11-09T14:39:47.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422864/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422864/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","LIBOR: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to ensure that every region and constituent part of the UK benefits from money raised from Libor fines.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","12743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422865","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<br /><p>As part of the on-going thinking for the future and planning to move to regional centres, HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) has been looking at each region across the country in turn, taking into account local economic issues, business requirements, impact on current workforce and location principles.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-26T16:20:13.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422865/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422865/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Revenue and Customs: Cumbernauld","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 25 June 2015 to Questions 3601 and 3602, if he will make an assessment of the potential economic effect on Cumbernauld of moving the HM Revenue and Customs office there elsewhere, as proposed in Building our Future - Continuing the Conversation, published in May 2015.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart McDonald","12759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422866","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>The Government is making changes to Tax Credits which will help put welfare spending on a more sustainable path. The Government wants to move from a low wage, high tax, high welfare society to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society.</p><br /><p>We know that work is the best route out of poverty. The intended impact of these reforms is to incentivise work, ensure work always pays, and then allow people to keep more of what they earn.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-26T15:38:06.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422866/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422866/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the likely change to levels of child poverty resulting from reductions in tax credits in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","12891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422867","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>The impact of all the government’s policies on housing benefit is accounted for in the housing benefit forecast, which has been certified by the OBR.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-26T15:36:57.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422867/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422867/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the effect of reductions in tax credits on levels of housing benefit paid out in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","12892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422868","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials receive representations and have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><br /><p>As has been the practice adopted by previous Administrations it is not Government policy to normally release details of such meetings.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","12821 ; 12880","2015-10-29T15:19:19.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422868/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422868/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received on insurers not giving details of no claims bonuses to customers in their renewal notice.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","12879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422869","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials receive representations and have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><br /><p>As has been the practice adopted by previous Administrations it is not Government policy to normally release details of such meetings.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","12821 ; 12879","2015-10-29T15:19:19.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422869/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422869/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received on insurers signing customers up to future auto-renewals without the option to opt out.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","12880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422870","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>The Government is committed to addressing the affordability of housing and making the aspiration of home ownership a reality for as many households as possible. At Budget 2014, the Help to Buy: equity loan scheme was extended to 2020 and the Government also intends to support younger buyers through delivering 200,000 Starter Homes by 2020, to be sold at a 20% discount for first time buyers under 40. These measures will also be supported by the launch of a Help to Buy: ISA through which the Government will top up mortgage deposit savings for first time buyers by 25% up to a maximum of £3,000.</p><p><br> Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at: <a href="http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm</a></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","12889","2015-10-26T15:35:18.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422870/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422870/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what support he plans to provide to home-buyers after the end of the mortgage guarantee scheme in 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","12888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422871","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>The Government is committed to addressing the affordability of housing and making the aspiration of home ownership a reality for as many households as possible. At Budget 2014, the Help to Buy: equity loan scheme was extended to 2020 and the Government also intends to support younger buyers through delivering 200,000 Starter Homes by 2020, to be sold at a 20% discount for first time buyers under 40. These measures will also be supported by the launch of a Help to Buy: ISA through which the Government will top up mortgage deposit savings for first time buyers by 25% up to a maximum of £3,000.</p><p><br> Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at: <a href="http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm</a></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","12888","2015-10-26T15:35:19.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422871/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422871/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with (a) his ministerial colleagues and (b) external organisations on the future of the mortgage guarantee scheme of the Help to Buy policy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","12889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422872","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>This is a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government.</p><br /><p>The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","13001 ; 13002 ; 13003 ; 13004","2015-10-29T15:05:33.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422872/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422872/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of auto-renewals on competition in the private motor insurance market.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","12882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422873","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>Funding for fire and rescue authorities, national resilience and other central programmes will be determined as part of the Spending Review.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-29T15:09:19.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422873/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422873/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Fire Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what budget reductions he plans to the fire and rescue service.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","12883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422874","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>The effective operation of Gift Aid, which enables charitable donations to be made free from tax, is a vitally important issue for Government, charities and their donors in all parts of the United Kingdom. The UK Government works closely with the charity sector to ensure that Gift Aid works effectively for charities and their donors.</p><p>We consulted the charity sector fully in advance of agreeing the arrangements for the continued operation of Gift Aid under the Scottish Rate of Income Tax, which will come into effect in April 2016. Under the agreed arrangements Gift Aid will continue to operate at UK-wide rates, a solution that means no extra complexity, uncertainty or administrative burden for the charity sector or donors.</p><br /><p>Similarly, we are fully committed to consulting the charity sector – in Scotland and the rest of the UK – to fully understand the impact of the devolution of income tax powers as proposed by Part 2 of the Scotland Bill 2015 ahead of agreeing arrangements for the continued operation of Gift Aid.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-26T15:41:09.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422874/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422874/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Gift Aid: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to Part 2 of the Scotland Bill 2015, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the planned transfer of income tax powers on the operation of Gift Aid in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","12909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422875","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-26","<p>The impact of the new National Living Wage and the end of the contracting out of National Insurance Contributionswill be considered during the Spending Review as part of an overall assessment of spending priorities and pressures across the public sector. The Spending Review will conclude on 25<sup>th</sup> November 2015.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-26T15:41:57.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422875/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422875/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-21","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what provision his Department has made for (a) payment of the national living wage by public sector employers and (b) the 3.4 per cent increase in Secondary National Insurance Contributions (NICs) from 2016-17 following the abolition of Contracted Out NICs.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","12910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422876","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Government intends to move to 100% business rates retention in England by the end of this Parliament. We have confirmed that as part of the new system there will continue to be redistribution of local tax revenue between authorities and protections in place for authorities that see their business rates income fall significantly. Over the coming months we will be working with local government on the details of the scheme.</p><p>Ahead of final decisions, it is too early to assess what the impact will be on individual areas or authorities, but before the start of the financial year, local authorities in the North-East estimated that the total business rates income for 2015-16 would be £854.58 million.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","12862 ; 12863 ; 12865 ; 13234","2015-10-29T17:22:45.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422876/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422876/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-21","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities he expects to lose 7.5 per cent of their business rate revenue after the introduction of his business rate reforms.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","12864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422877","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-29","<p>In 2013-14, the total business rates income raised in Newcastle upon Tyne was £128.5 million. Based on their own estimates, the total business rates income in 2015-16 is expected to be £154.1 million</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-29T15:11:28.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422877/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422877/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-21","Non-domestic Rates: Newcastle Upon Tyne","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much was raised by business rates in the Newcastle upon Tyne local authority area in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","12861"
